   <titles>
      <title>Basic Properties of Linear Transformations</title>
      <plain.title>Basic Properties</plain.title>
   </titles>
   <intro>
      <block>
         <block.body>
            <para>
               <para.body>Here we establish two basic properties of linear transformations.</para.body>
            </para>
            <ol>
               <li>
                  <para>
                     <para.body>A linear transformation <math>
                           <latex>L\from \RNr[n]\to \RNr[m]</latex>
                        </math> always maps the zero-vector of <math>
                           <latex>\RNr[n]</latex>
                        </math> to the zero-vector of <math>
                           <latex>\RNr[m]</latex>
                        </math>. – Whenever a function <math>
                           <latex>f\from \RNr[n]\to \RNr[m]</latex>
                        </math> fails to satisfy <math>
                           <latex>f(\Vect{0})=\Vect{0}</latex>
                        </math>, <math>
                           <latex>f</latex>
                        </math> can not be linear.</para.body>
                  </para>
               </li>
               <li>
                  <para>
                     <para.body>A function <math>
                           <latex>\RNr[n]\to \RNr[m]</latex>
                        </math> is linear transformation if and only if it sends each linear motion in <math>
                           <latex>\RNr[n]</latex>
                        </math> to a linear motion in <math>
                           <latex>\RNr[n]</latex>
                        </math>. – This is a geometric characterization of linear transformation.</para.body>
                  </para>
               </li>
            </ol>
         </block.body>
      </block>
   </intro>
